   <titles>
      <title>Solving a System of Linear Equations Geometrically - Preview</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Here we express, in geometrical terms, the structure of the simultaneous solutions of a system of linear equations. We recall that the solutions of a single linear equation</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>
					
					\begin{array}{cccccccccc}
\colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_{1}$}{\color{red}x_1} &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_{2}$}{\color{red}x_2} &amp; + &amp; \cdots &amp; \cdots &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_{n}$}{\color{red}x_n} &amp; = &amp; c \\
\end{array}
					
				</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>form a hyperplane which is perpendicular to the vector <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{n}:= (a_1,\dots ,a_n)</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <media type="image" active="1" inline="0">
                     <img src="ims/LinearEqSingle.gif" height="255" width="359"/>
                  </media>
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Illustration</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Of the solution set of the linear equation</para.body>
                     </para>
                     <math.display>
                        <latex>
							
					\begin{array}{cccccccccc}
\colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_{1}$}{\color{red}x_1} &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_{2}$}{\color{red}x_2} &amp; + &amp; \cdots &amp; \cdots &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_{n}$}{\color{red}x_n} &amp; = &amp; c \\
\end{array}
					
						</latex>
                     </math.display>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Here we assume tacitly that the normal vector <math>
                              <latex>\mathbf{n}:= (a_1,\dots ,a_n)</latex>
                           </math> is not the 0-vector.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>The simultaneous solutions of two linear equations</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>
					
					\begin{array}{cccccccccc}
\colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_{1}$}{\color{red}x_1} &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_{2}$}{\color{red}x_2} &amp; + &amp; \cdots &amp; \cdots &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_{n}$}{\color{red}x_n} &amp; = &amp; c \\
					\colorbox{lightgreen}{$b_{1}$}{\color{red}x_1} &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$b_{2}$}{\color{red}x_2} &amp; + &amp; \cdots &amp; \cdots &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$b_{n}$}{\color{red}x_n} &amp; = &amp; d
\end{array}
					
				</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>form the intersection of two hyperplanes. When forming such an intersection of hyperplanes, one of several distinct situations can occur. Let's illustrate this for equations in 3 unknowns.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>First case</strong> the normal vectors <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{n}_1:= (a_1,a_2 ,a_3)</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{n}_2 := (b_1,b_2,b_3)</latex>
                  </math> are not parallel. Therefore, the associated hyperplanes are not parallel and, as a consequence, the simultaneous solutions of the two equations form the intersection of the two planes. It always is a line.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                     <img src="ims/LinearEqsTwo.gif" height="281" width="333"/>
                  </media>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>Second case</strong> the two hyperplanes are parallel and distinct. There is no point that belongs to both hyperplanes. Therefore there is no simultaneous solution of the given system of two linear equations.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                     <img src="ims/LinearEqsTwoParallel.gif" height="350" width="377"/>
                  </media>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>Third case</strong> the two hyperplanes are identical. This situation is a sibling of the second case. Only this time, the solutions of one equation also solve the other. So the simultaneous solutions of the given equations form a plane.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>In a system of <math>
                     <latex>m</latex>
                  </math> linear equations in <math>
                     <latex>n</latex>
                  </math> unknowns, the solutions of each one of them form a hyperplane in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math>. Therefore the simultaneous solutions of the system form exactly the intersection of all of these hyperplanes.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
